[1] Indonesia
Date: 7 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua 5 Mar 2004 via China View Sun 7 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2004-03/05/content_1348008.htm>

Death toll of dengue fever reaches 389 in Indonesia
----------------------------------------------
The death toll from dengue fever across Indonesia since January this
year [2004] has reached 389 and the sufferers increased to 226 013,
said Mariani Reksoprojo, a spokeswoman of the Health Ministry, on
Friday. She said that Jakarta is still the area with the most
infections.
3 ministries -- ministries of health, the people's welfare and
poverty alleviation, as well home affairs -- coordinated with all
provincial governments to step up efforts to stop the spread of the
outbreak. "The minister of health has asked hospitals to immediately
help new patients," Reksoprojo added.
Syafei Achmad, secretary general of the prevention of the infectious
disease under the Health Ministry, said that some 89 percent of the
sufferers are in good condition. The official said that the toll of
death and suffering in some provinces, such as Eastern Nusa Tenggara,
Jambi, and Yogyakarta, has declined.
The recent attack was different from the normal 5-year cycle [because
of] the change of rainy season from October, November, and December
to January and February, he said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[26 of Indonesia's 32 provinces are affected, and the predominant
serotype is dengue-3, but all 4 serotypes are involved. - Mod.JW]
******
[2] Singapore
Date: 7 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AP in Borneo Bulletin Fri 5 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.brunei-online.com/bb/fri/mar5w6.htm>

Singapore steps up dengue fever checks
-------------------------------------------
Singapore plans to step up dengue fever checks because of an outbreak
in neighbouring Indonesia that has killed over 340 people [389 - see
above] and sickened around 20 000 [this must be the number
hospitalized out of the more than 200 000 reported above. - Mod.JW].
Singapore's own cases of the disease have declined, with the
city-state reporting 560 cases in the first 2 months of 2004, down
from 688 in the same period of 2003, the National Environment Agency
said.
"The overall situation is under control and showing signs of
improvement," it said in a statement late Wednesday. But the agency,
responsible for monitoring public health in the city-state, said it
would step up enforcement and surveillance to prevent the
mosquito-borne illness from spreading.
Singapore issues fines for people who leave watering cans, buckets,
and other containers with stagnant water in the open. During February
2004, the High Court fined a man 6000 Singapore dollars (US$3530) for
leaving a water-filled plastic pail lid outside his residence.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
